**It does look good. The only thing I can think of is your weight distribution. Do you feel your weight go down through your sitting bones?

There is other things that you can’t gather from a picture. You need to be relaxed and feel free all the way through your arms and shoulders. Maybe a slight lean forward from where you are but not far.

I can’t see your feet either. Generally my right foot is at the pedal and my left foot is below my knee. Between the 2 feet and my bum I have 3 points of support when playing. The only time I lean back is if both hands are playing in the middle of the keyboard and I will sometimes lean forward if both hands are at the extreme right an left of the keys.

Your weight should distribute evenly between your bum bones unless you need to tilt left or right when both hands are playing high or low.

A couple of things you could check is the Taubman approach. See if they’ve got tips. That’s the method my teacher uses. Also Anderson technique.

There is a really sad book I read a while ago called ‘What Every Pianist Needs to Know About the Body’ by Thomas Mark. Might be worth a read. It talks about how your mind should map your body.

Good luck with it though. It’s a real shame when people can’t pursue their dreams or passions because of something like this. I have a friend who was an excellent golfer and had to give it up because of his back.

**The only time this is the case is with a tied note. If a note was sharped in the previous bar and tied to the next bar… it’s still sharp… but only so long as it’s still tied.

If you have to re-articulate that same note, it will need another sharp to keep it sharp.**
